[_Ceratocystis fimbriata_ (Cf) is currently considered a fungal species complex. The different species/strains cause rots, wilts and cankers on many hosts, including important crop and forest species, but vary in host specificity. The sweet potato strain of Cf has a narrow host range; sweet potato (_Ipomoea batatas_) and "morning glories" mentioned above belong to genera in the family Convolvulaceae.

CF strains are soilborne and also spread by water, mechanical means (for example on cutting tools) and with planting material (cuttings, seedlings). Beetles have been reported as important vectors in some hosts.

Disease management of soil borne fungi may include phytosanitary measures, crop rotation and use of certified disease-free planting material. Fungicides are generally not very effective, but may be helpful as treatments for seedlings or scions before release for planting. Genetic resistance is generally considered the best means of control, and sweet potato cultivars with reduced black rot sensitivity are available.

